# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: car
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The **1980s oil glut** was a significant surplus of crude oil caused by falling demand following the 1970s energy crisis.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The world price of oil had peaked in 1980 at over US$35 per barrel (equivalent to $137 per barrel in 2025 dollars, when adjusted for inflation); it fell in 1986 from $27 to below $10 ($79 to $29 in 2025 dollars).
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The glut began in the early 1980s as a result of slowed economic activity in industrial countries due to the crises of the 1970s, especially in 1973 and 1979, and the energy conservation (including replacing oil in some applications with other fuels) spurred by high fuel prices.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The inflation-adjusted real 2004 dollar value of oil fell from an average of $78.2 in 1981 to an average of $26.8 per barrel in 1986.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In June 1981, *The New York Times* proclaimed that an "oil glut" had arrived and *Time* stated that "the world temporarily floats in a glut of oil".
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] However, *The New York Times* warned the next week that the word "glut" was misleading, and that temporary surpluses had brought down prices somewhat, but prices were still well above pre-energy crisis levels.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] This sentiment was echoed in November 1981, when the CEO of Exxon also characterized the glut as a temporary surplus, and that the word "glut" was an example of "our American penchant for exaggerated language".
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] He wrote that the main cause of the glut was declining consumption.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In the United States, Europe, and Japan, oil consumption had fallen 13% from 1979 to 1981, "in part, in reaction to the very large increases in oil prices by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and other oil exporters", continuing a trend begun during the 1973 price increases.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] After 1980, reduced demand and increased production produced a glut on the world market.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The result was a six-year decline in the price of oil, which reduced the price by half in 1986 alone.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] During the 1980s, reliance on Middle East production dwindled as commercial exploration developed major non-OPEC oilfields in Siberia, Alaska, the North Sea, and the Gulf of Mexico, and the Soviet Union became the world's largest producer of oil.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Smaller non-OPEC producers including Brazil, Egypt, India, Malaysia, and Oman doubled their output between 1979 and 1985, to a total of 3 million barrels per day.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] President Jimmy Carter signed an executive order to remove price controls from petroleum products by October 1981 so that prices would be wholly determined by the free market.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Carter's successor, Ronald Reagan, signed an executive order on 28 January 1981, which enacted that reform immediately, allowing the free market to adjust oil prices in the United States.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] That ended the withdrawal of old oil from the market and artificial scarcity, which encouraged an increase in oil production.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Additionally, the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System began pumping oil in 1977.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The Alaskan Prudhoe Bay Oil Field entered peak production, supplying 2 million bpd of crude oil in 1988, 25 percent of all U.S. oil production.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Phillips Petroleum discovered oil in the Chalk Group at Ekofisk, in Norwegian waters in the central North Sea.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Discoveries increased exponentially in the 1970s and 1980s, and new fields were developed throughout the continental shelf.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] From 1980 to 1986, OPEC decreased oil production several times in an attempt to maintain oil's high prices.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] However, it failed to hold on to its preeminent position, and by 1981, its production was surpassed by non-OPEC countries.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] OPEC had seen its share of the world market drop to less than a third in 1985, from about half during the 1970s.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In February 1982, the *Boston Globe* reported that OPEC's production, which had previously peaked in 1977, was at its lowest level since 1969.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Non-OPEC nations were at that time supplying most of the West's imports.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] OPEC's membership began to have divided opinions over what actions to take.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In September 1985, Saudi Arabia became unhappy with de facto propping up prices by lowering its own production in the face of high output from elsewhere in OPEC.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In 1985, daily output was around 3.5 million bpd, down from around 10 million in 1981.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] During this period, OPEC members were supposed to meet production quotas in order to maintain price stability; however, many countries inflated their reserves to achieve higher quotas, cheated, or outright refused to accord with the quotas.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In 1985, the Saudis tired of this behavior and decided to punish the undisciplined OPEC countries.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The Saudis abandoned their role as swing producer and began producing at full capacity, creating a "huge surplus that angered many of their colleagues in OPEC".
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] High-cost oil production facilities became less or even not profitable.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Oil prices as a result fell to as low as $7 per barrel.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] OPEC had relied on the price inelasticity of demand of oil to maintain high consumption, but underestimated the extent to which other sources of supply would become profitable as prices increased.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Electricity generation from coal, nuclear power and natural gas; home heating from natural gas; and ethanol blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] New passenger car fuel economy in the United States changed from 14 miles per US gallon (17 L/100 km) in 1975 to 22 miles per US gallon (11 L/100 km) in 1982, a change of more than 50 percent.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The United States imported 28 percent of its oil in 1982 and 1983, down from 46.5 percent in 1977, due to lower consumption.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] France had relied to a significant extent on imported petroleum for electricity production prior to the 1973 oil price shock.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The "Messmer Plan" implemented under prime minister Pierre Messmer called for a massive expansion of nuclear power using license built pressurized water reactors instead of the older French UNGG reactors.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The 1986 oil price collapse benefited oil-consuming countries such as the United States and Japan, countries in Europe, and developing nations but represented a serious loss in revenue for oil-producing countries in Northern Europe, the Soviet Union, and OPEC.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In 1981, before the brunt of the glut, *Time Magazine* wrote that in general, "A glut of crude causes tighter development budgets" in some oil-exporting nations.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Mexico had an economic and debt crisis in 1982.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The Venezuelan economy contracted and inflation levels (consumer price inflation) rose, remaining between 6 and 12% from 1982 to 1986.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The crisis resulted in the 1989 Caracazo protests.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Iraq had fought a long and costly war against Iran and had particularly weak revenues.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] It was upset by Kuwait contributing to the glut and allegedly pumping oil from the Rumaila field below their common border.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990, planning to increase reserves and revenues and cancel the debt, resulting in the first Gulf War.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The glut directed Algeria into an economic recession and directly influenced the politics: the authoritarian regime of Chadli Bendjedid had to compromise with Islamic opposition in 1984 and start economic reforms dismantling socialism in 1987.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] After the 1988 October Riots he reformed the constitution twice, liberalized the political space amid growing discontent, and was ousted from office by the military after his party lost the first multi-party elections to Islamists, eventually leading to the Algerian Civil War.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The Soviet Union had become a major oil producer before the glut.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The drop of oil prices contributed to the nation's final collapse.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In the United States, domestic exploration and the number of active drilling rigs were cut dramatically.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In late 1985, there were nearly 2,300 rigs drilling wells; a year later, there were barely 1,000.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] The number of U.S. petroleum producers decreased from 11,370 in 1985 to 5,231 in 1989, according to data from the Independent Petroleum Association of America.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Oil producers held back on the search for new oilfields for fear of losing on their investments.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] In May 2007, companies like ExxonMobil were not making nearly the investment in finding new oil that they did in 1981.
[src:car/1980s-oil-glut] Canada responded to high energy prices in the 1970s with the National Energy Program (NEP) in 1980.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] A **2+2** (also **2-plus-2**) is a car-body style that has a seat each for the driver and front passenger, and two rear seats.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] The latter may be individual "bucket" seats, fold-downs, or a full-width "bucketed" bench seat, but always with less leg room than either the front seats or a standard two-door car.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] The style is different from four- or five-seat automobiles having normal-size rear seats, with second-row 2+2 seating typically only suitable for children or occasional use.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] By standard definition, all cars in the 2+2 category have two front seats and two rear seats.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] Other common characteristics for 2+2 cars include relatively little room for the rear passengers and a "streamlined" body with two doors.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] While 2+2 seating is most commonly associated with coupés, especially those which strongly favour front passenger seating such as sports cars and grand tourer, certain convertibles with "auxiliary"-type rear seats may also be regarded as 2+2s.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] Some vehicles (such as the TVR Cerbera and Toyota iQ) have been marketed as "3+1" due to their front passenger seat having more space for forward adjustment than the driver's, allowing for more leg room for one rear-seat passenger.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] There are many coupés which meet the definition of a 2+2 but are not described by their manufacturers as such.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] This is because the term *2+2* is most often used to distinguish cars with what typically amounts to auxiliary rear seating, at times enlarged from a two-seat version of the same model to accommodate it, such as the Jaguar E-type fixed-head coupé 2+2.
[src:car/2-2-car-body-style] Other similar examples of stretched two-seaters include the Lotus Elan +2, Mazda RX-8, and Nissan 280ZX 2+2.
[src:car/a-segment] The **A-segment** is the first category in the passenger car classification system defined by the European Commission.
[src:car/a-segment] It is used for **city cars**, the smallest category of passenger cars defined.
[src:car/a-segment] A-segment sales represented approximately 4.2% of the European market in 2024.
[src:car/a-segment] It is approximately equivalent to the kei car class in Japan.
[src:car/a-segment] As of 2021, the A-segment category size spans from approximately 2.7 metres (110 in) to 3.7 metres (150 in).
[src:car/a-segment] Body styles for A-segment cars in Europe have historically nearly always been hatchbacks.
[src:car/a-segment] But as crossovers gain popularity, new models have begun to shift to resemble crossovers.
[src:car/a-segment] Examples of crossover city cars include Suzuki Ignis and Toyota Aygo X.
[src:car/a-segment] Other body styles such as sedans have only a few models present in this segment because these shapes largely prove impractical at typical A-segment dimensions.
[src:car/a-segment] A-segment cars are traditionally offered with manual transmission as the sole transmission option.
[src:car/a-segment] Beginning in the 2010s, automatic options are increasingly available.
[src:car/a-segment] Some newer models most often utilize CVTs, while a small number of manufacturers also offer automated manual transmissions.
[src:car/a-segment] The engines of A-segment cars commonly range from 1.0 to 1.4 litres, either in inline-four or three configuration.
[src:car/a-segment] Newer models may have turbocharged and/or hybrid engines with a particular emphasis on higher fuel efficiency.
[src:car/a-segment] In 2020 the ten highest selling A-segment cars in Europe were Fiat Panda, Fiat 500, Toyota Aygo, Renault Twingo, Volkswagen Up!, Hyundai i10, Kia Picanto, Peugeot 108, Citroën C1 and Suzuki Ignis.
[src:car/a-segment] 2019 - In 2019, sales of minicars were down 2% compared to a total market gain of 1% which means this segment now makes up 7.7% of the total European car market at 1.21 million sales, down from 8% in 2018.
[src:car/a-segment] And with margins on minicars under pressure due to increased costs to comply with stricter safety and emissions standards, manufacturers are scaling back investments in to minicars or switching to an EV-only strategy.
[src:car/a-segment] In Italy, A-segment cars represented 16.4% of car sales in the first half of 2019.
[src:car/a-segment] 2020 - European sales of minicars were down by a third in 2020, which translates to nearly 400,000 fewer sales and means the segment loses market share as the overall market is down 24%.
[src:car/a-segment] As a result, this segment now makes up 6.8% of the total European car market, down from 7.7% last year.
[src:car/a-segment] And their share is expected to shrink further in coming years, as manufacturers are pulling out of this segment or switching their models to EV-only.
[src:car/a-segment] This is a result of increasing costs to comply with stricter safety and especially emissions standards, which makes minicars nearly unprofitable, especially considering that for most models from European brands this is the only market.
[src:car/a-segment] In the United States, minicar segment cars represented 0.5% of the market share.
[src:car/a-segment] In 2020 the highest selling minicar segment cars in the U.S. were the Chevrolet Spark, Mitsubishi Mirage and Mini Cooper.
[src:car/a-segment] In India, historically the A-segment cars had the highest sales.
[src:car/a-segment] Sales have been in decline in recent years, falling from 70,000 sales per month in 2014 to 47,000 sales per month in 2016.
[src:car/a-segment] As of 2019, several A-segment cars had successes outside Europe, such as Hyundai Grand i10, Honda Brio, Kia Picanto, Tata Tiago, Toyota Wigo, Suzuki Celerio, Suzuki Wagon R, Suzuki/Maruti Alto, Ford Figo, Smart ForTwo, Citroën C1, Peugeot 108, and modern Fiat 500.
[src:car/abbey-1922-automobile] The **Abbey** was a short-lived friction drive car assembled by the Abbey Auto Engineering Co.
[src:car/abbey-1922-automobile] It used a 10.8 hp 1498 cc Coventry-Simplex engine.
[src:car/abbey-1922-automobile] It was built in 1922 only and cost £315.
[src:car/abbey-1922-automobile] It also had Marles steering gear and friction drive.
[src:car/abbey-1922-automobile] After 1922 the car may have been sold as the Lewis.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The **accident data recorder** (**ADR**, German commonly abbr.: **UDS**, also accident (data) writer) is an independent electronic device that records before, during, and after a traffic accident relevant data and thus resembles a flight recorder.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] It can be installed in motor vehicles (cars, trucks, buses, motorcycles, trams, and special vehicles) on a voluntary basis in order to obtain more accurate information about the events in an accident.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In some countries there are regulations for mandatory installation in different vehicles.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The accident data recorder constantly records various data of the vehicle (such as speed, direction of travel, longitudinal and transverse vehicle acceleration, status of the lights, turn signals and braking, etc.) and records them for some time before they are automatically cleared.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In the case of an accident (this is detected by a strong acceleration of the vehicle as a result of an impulse), certain periods of time (usually in the two-digit seconds range) remain permanently stored before and after an event.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] This makes it much easier to reconstruct events after an accident, so that if necessary the question of fault can be clarified.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Many vehicles of authorities (such as police or ambulance) are equipped with them, as it often comes to assist with disputes that pertain to collisions during high priority calls as well as compliance with applicable laws and regulations.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] A side effect of vehicles equipped with UDS is that drivers behave more cautiously on the road.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] According to a survey by the EU Transport Commission, UDS users experienced a 20 to 30 percent decline in traffic accidents.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The accident data recorder is often used by experts or institutions in crash tests as a measuring device.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The installation (also later) costs about 700 euros and can lead to a deduction for some insurance policies.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The accident data recorder can be read by an expert via interface cable.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The accident data recorder (older generations) has a switch with which the driver can delete the stored data immediately after an accident so as not to burden himself with the later question of guilt.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] However, this feature may be disabled, for example for use in company vehicles.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Accident data recorders work to measure the accelerations, depending on the equipment in two or three spatial directions, with micromechanical sensors.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Often several sensor systems with different resolutions are used in order to be able to log both the driving dynamic processes and the collision dynamics.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Higher-class systems also offer a possibility for measuring the rotational movements as well as the vehicle speed as well as highly specific measurements to the amount of pressure applied on different controls.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The latter can e.g. be calculated from the signal of the vehicle's wheel speed sensor.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The recording of any signals that are available on the vehicle's own CAN bus, is possible with higher-class devices as well as the detection of a GPS signal for position and speed determination.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Depending on the manufacturer, about 20 to 30 s are recorded before and 10 to 15 s after an event.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Are known today (as of 2018) in the German-speaking countries essentially two suitable for retrofitting accident data recorder.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Blacktrack Ltd. offers a low-cost solution, which is mainly used by the insurance industry (e.g.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] By contrast, the UDS-AT developed by the company consortium Peter Systemtechnik GmbH and Kast GmbH offers extended possibilities of recording and integration into a vehicle.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Residual path recording devices (RAG) from Mobatime AG are external devices that rely on existing on-board signals (distance, speed, operating states of status inputs) and store them in a ring buffer for at least the last 12 km.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In contrast to an accident data recorder, they do not have their own measuring sensors.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In The US, The legal landscape concerning EDRs and ADRs involves an interplay of constitutional principles, particularly the Fourth Amendment's protections against unreasonable searches and seizures.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Notably, legal precedents have established exceptions for vehicles, allowing law enforcement to conduct searches without a warrant if probable cause exists.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] This precedent has been cited in debates regarding the warrantless access of data stored in ADRs.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Recent Supreme Court cases, notably Riley v.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] U.S., have extended Fourth Amendment protections to digital data, including cell phone information and location data.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] However, the direct application of these rulings to ADRs remains unclear, contributing to a disparity in legal standards regarding the privacy of car data.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Statutory regulations, such as the Electronic Communications Privacy Act (ECPA), have provided limited protections to third-party-held data, raising questions about their applicability to car manufacturers and ADRs specifically.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Several states have enacted laws supplementing federal regulations to safeguard car data, although the consistency and effectiveness of these measures vary across jurisdictions.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Ongoing Efforts such as the Driver Privacy Act (DPA) and other safeguards aim to regulate access to black box information in vehicles.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] However, the uniformity in mandating warrants for data access remains a subject of debate and potential future legislative action.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Many states have applicable statutes in which having a self-deletion switch on such a device could be considered tampering with evidence.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] This is yet to be brought up in any current caselaw as the ADRs that are equipped with such a device are not commonplace in the US.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Reading out the data of an accident data recorder requires special software.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The evaluation and interpretation of measurement data of a traffic accident require special knowledge in the areas of vehicle dynamics, accident reconstruction, metrology and last but not least the accident data storage technology itself.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] For UDS there is a separate order area for expert witnesses in Germany.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The picture on the right shows the (unprocessed) data curves of a real accident recorded with a UDS.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The measured accelerations, the speed and various status channels are plotted over time.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] It can be seen, for example, that vehicle special signals were switched on prior to the collision and the driver was previously still applying the brake.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The nowadays known accident data recorder was invented by Mannesmann Kienzle GmbH, which applied for a patent in 1992.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The development began in Germany in the early 1980s with the two companies MBB and Kienzle, who pursued different concepts.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In general, the black box was taken as a model, which was developed in the early 1950s in Australia by David Warren.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Already in 1973, General Motors applied for a patent for a "vehicle crash recorder".
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Mannesmann Kienzle delivered the first accident data recorder in early 1993.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In motorsport, accident data recorders (ADR) must be used in various series as specified by the FIA.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Starting with the 2015 season, the use of an ADR in the Formula 4 championship was compulsory.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In the higher series, the use has been mandatory for some time.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In addition to the data of the acceleration sensors mounted on the vehicle, the loads on the driver are also measured with an in-ear accelerometer.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Due to the higher speeds in formula sports compared to road traffic, the sensors have a measuring range of ± 150 g with a resolution of 0.1 g.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] With an event duration of 30 s, 10 events can be stored.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Both in a flight recorder and in a UDS, the constantly recorded data runs in a ring buffer.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] However, the flight recorder usually records for longer periods of 17 to 25 hours.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] In contrast, the UDS only saves a few seconds before and after an event is triggered (e.g. collision) permanently.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] The term *drive data recorder* is generally understood to mean a continuous and permanently available recording of data and signals during the operation of a vehicle, independently of an accident.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Such systems are often used in locomotives or trams.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Often, however, an electronic logbook is referred to as drive data recorder.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Dashcams are sometimes referred to as drive data recorder or *video event data recorder* (VEDR).
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] A so-called *Event Data Recorder* (EDR) is not an accident data recorder in the sense of an autonomous, more or less vehicle-independent device, since an EDR is usually an additional electronic module in an existing control device (e.g. from the Airbag) in a car.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] EDRs rely exclusively on on-board signals, while UDS have their own inertial sensors.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] Vehicles with airbag systems store accident-relevant data (impact accelerations, belt buckle conditions, seat positions, trip times) in the internal memory of the tripping electronics.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] However, the data size varies depending on the manufacturer and only extends over a few seconds or fractions.
[src:car/accident-data-recorder] NHTSA regulations call for uniform data sets for all systems manufactured from 2010 onwards.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] The **Ackermann steering geometry** (also called **Ackermann's steering trapezium**) is a geometric arrangement of linkages in the steering of a car or other vehicle designed to solve the problem of wheels on the inside and outside of a turn needing to trace out circles of different radii.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] It was invented by the German carriage builder Georg Lankensperger in Munich in 1816, then patented by his agent in England, Rudolph Ackermann (1764–1834) in 1818 for horse-drawn carriages.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] Erasmus Darwin may have a prior claim as the inventor dating from 1758.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] He devised his steering system because he was injured when a carriage tipped over.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] The first requirement of any steering geometry is to avoid the need for tyres to slip sideways when following the path around a curve.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] The geometrical solution to this is for all wheels to have their axles arranged as radii of circles with a common centre point.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] As the rear wheels are fixed, this centre point must be on a line extended from the rear axle and where the axis of one front wheel meets that line, so must the other.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] A billy cart or four-wheel wagon, whose front axles are fixed to a solid beam with a central pivot, easily meets this condition but requires considerable steering effort because of the fore-and-aft movement of the wheels, and is heavily influenced by road surface variations.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] Rather than the preceding "turntable" steering, Ackermann geometry gives each front wheel hub its own pivoted carrier (on solid axles this pivot is called a kingpin but on more complex suspension it may be separate upper and lower pivots), close to its hub.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] While more complex, this arrangement enhances controllability by reducing the fore-and-aft travel of the steered wheels.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] The whole arrangement of the axle, steering arms and tie rod forms a trapezium when the wheels are set straight ahead (see picture).
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] When the wheels are turned, the inner wheel turns farther than the outer wheel.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] A simple approximation to perfect Ackermann steering geometry may be generated by moving the steering arm pivot points inward so as to lie on a line drawn between the steering kingpins, which are the hub carrier pivot points, and the centre of the rear axle.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] The steering arm pivot points are joined by a rigid bar called the **tie rod**.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] With perfect Ackermann, at any angle of steering, the centre point of all of the circles traced by all wheels will lie at a common point.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] Modern cars do not use *pure* Ackermann steering, partly because it ignores important dynamic and compliant effects, but the principle is sound for low-speed maneuvers.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] Some racing cars use reverse Ackermann geometry to compensate for the large difference in slip angle between the inner and outer front tires while cornering at high speed.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] The use of such geometry helps reduce tire temperatures during high-speed cornering but compromises performance in low-speed maneuvers.
[src:car/ackermann-steering-geometry] The Ackermann condition of vehicle train is fulfilled when both the vehicle wheel and the trailer wheel axes are pointing to the theoretical turning center (momentan centrum).
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] An **active rollover protection** (**ARP**), is a system that recognizes impending rollover and selectively applies brakes to resist.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] ARP builds on electronic stability control and its three chassis control systems already on the vehicle – anti-lock braking system, traction control and yaw control.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] ARP adds another function: detection of an impending rollover.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] Excessive lateral force, generated by excessive speed in a turn, may result in a rollover.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] ARP automatically responds whenever it detects a potential rollover.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] ARP rapidly applies the brakes with a high burst of pressure to the appropriate wheels and sometimes decreases the engine torque to interrupt the rollover before it occurs.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] Rollovers can also occur when the vehicle is knocked into a stationary object such as a curb.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] In these so-called "trip events", a vehicle hit from the side but kept from moving laterally by a curb would produce a moment about the center of gravity sufficient to produce a rollover.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] To counteract this, rollover stability systems have begun to incorporate an active suspension system in rollover protection.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] To accomplish this, the onboard computer uses data from the inertial measurement unit (IMU) to determine when a vehicle is in a rollover condition independent of yaw rate and vehicle speed.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] When the computer determines that the vehicle is at risk of rollover, it calculates the direction of roll and activates the active suspension system.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] The force produced in the suspension creates a moment (torque) opposite to that created by the lateral force, and keeps the vehicle safe.
[src:car/active-rollover-protection] The phrase is also used for active roll over bars for convertible cars, such as the Volkswagen Beetle, which can detect potential roll-over situations and automatically raises rollover bars hidden in the rear head restraints in a fraction of a second.
[src:car/car] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:car/car] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:car/car] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:car/car] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:car/car] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:car/car] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:car/car] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:car/car] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:car/car] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:car/car] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:car/car] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:car/car] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:car/car] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:car/car] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:car/car] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:car/car] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:car/car] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:car/car] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:car/car] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:car/car] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:car/car] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:car/car] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:car/car] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:car/car] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:car/car] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:car/car] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:car/car] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:car/car] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:car/car] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:car/car] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:car/car] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:car/car] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:car/car] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:car/car] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:car/car] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:car/car] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:car/car] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:car/car] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:car/car] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:car/car] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:car/car] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:car/car] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:car/car] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:car/car] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:car/car] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:car/car] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:car/car] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:car/car] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:car/car] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:car/car] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:car/car] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:car/car] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:car/car] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:car/car] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:car/car] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:car/car] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:car/car] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:car/car] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:car/car] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:car/car] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:car/car] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:car/car] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:car/car] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:car/car] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:car/car] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:car/car] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:car/car] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:car/car] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:car/car] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:car/car] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:car/car] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:car/car] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:car/car] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:car/car] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:car/car] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:car/car] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:car/car] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:car/car] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:car/car] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:car/car] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:car/car] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:car/car] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:car/car] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:car/car] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:car/car] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:car/car] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:car/car] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:car/car] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:car/car] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:car/car] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:car/car] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:car/car] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:car/car] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:car/car] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:car/car] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:car/car] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:car/car] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:car/car] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:car/car] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:car/car] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:car/car] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:car/car] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:car/car] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:car/car] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:car/car] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:car/car] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:car/car] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:car/car] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:car/car] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:car/car] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:car/car] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:car/car] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:car/car] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:car/car] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:car/car] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:car/car] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:car/car] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:car/car] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:car/car] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:car/car] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:car/car] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:car/car] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:car/car] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:car/car] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:car/car] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:car/car] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:car/car] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:car/car] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:car/car] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:car/car] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:car/car] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:car/car] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:car/car] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:car/car] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:car/car] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:car/car] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:car/car] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:car/car] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:car/car] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:car/car] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:car/car] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:car/car] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:car/car] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:car/car] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:car/car] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:car/car] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:car/car] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:car/car] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:car/car] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:car/car] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:car/car] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:car/car] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:car/car] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:car/car] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:car/car] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:car/car] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:car/car] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:car/car] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:car/car] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:car/car] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:car/car] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:car/car] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:car/car] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:car/car] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:car/car] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:car/car] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:car/car] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:car/car] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:car/car] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:car/car] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:car/car] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:car/car] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:car/car] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:car/car] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:car/car] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:car/car] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:car/car] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:car/car] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:car/car] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:car/car] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:car/car] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:car/car] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:car/car] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:car/car] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:car/car] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:car/car] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:car/car] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:car/car] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:car/car] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:car/car] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:car/car] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:car/car] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:car/car] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:car/car] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:car/car] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:car/car] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:car/car] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:car/car] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:car/car] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:car/car] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:car/car] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:car/car] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:car/car] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:car/car] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:car/car] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:car/car] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:car/car] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:car/car] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:car/car] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:car/car] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:car/car] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:car/car] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:car/car] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:car/car] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:car/car] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:car/car] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:car/car] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:car/car] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:car/car] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:car/car] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:car/car] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:car/car] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:car/car] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:car/car] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:car/car] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:car/car] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:car/car] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:car/car] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:car/car] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:car/car] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
